{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"152"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/152"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.38,0.06,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/152"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"3884"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8143"},{"type":"tags","id":"8149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12365"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up after breast cancer treatment. She was diagnosed with invasive ductal carcinoma found during routine screening mammography. Tests revealed oestrogen receptor positive, progesterone receptor positive, and HER-2 receptor negative status. She subsequently underwent a mastectomy and sentinel lymph node biopsy, which showed no nodal involvement. She has a medical history of hypertension and dyslipidaemia. Her regular medications include perindopril and rosuvastatin. Her last menstrual period was four years ago. Her mother had breast cancer at the age of 60 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no signs of recurrence or further spread.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate adjuvant treatment to offer this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anastrozole","Tamoxifen","Trastuzumab","Paclitaxel + doxorubicin","Cyclophosphamide"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s hormone receptor status indicates a role for adjuvant endocrine therapy with either tamoxifen (a selective oestrogen receptor modulator) or an aromatase inhibitor such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eanastrozole\u003C/strong\u003E. In post-menopausal women, the vast majority of oestrogen is formed by the conversion of androgens (synthesised in the adrenal glands) by aromatase enzymes in the mammary and adipose tissues, which can be effectively suppressed by an aromatase inhibitor. This approach has been shown to be at least as effective as tamoxifen in meta-analyses, with a favourable side effect profile, and as such has become the standard first-line treatment in the post-menopausal population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETamoxifen\u003C/strong\u003E remains first-line in the pre-menopausal population, in whom ovarian oestrogen synthesis can overwhelm the effect of aromatase inhibitor monotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrastuzumab\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in the treatment of HER-2 receptor positive cancer. This patient\u0027s cancer is HER-2 negative, so trastuzumab would not be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaclitaxel + doxorubicin\u003C/strong\u003E is a combination chemotherapy regimen sometimes used in breast cancer treatment. However, for this patient with early-stage, hormone receptor-positive breast cancer and no nodal involvement, endocrine therapy alone is likely sufficient without the need for chemotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclophosphamide\u003C/strong\u003E is an alkylating agent which is often used in combination with other chemotherapy treatments. However, for this patient with early-stage, hormone receptor-positive breast cancer and no nodal involvement, endocrine therapy alone is likely sufficient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that the patient underwent a sentinel lymph node biopsy, which is now the standard of care for axillary staging in early breast cancer. This procedure is less invasive than a full axillary node clearance and has a lower risk of complications such as lymphoedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aromatase inhibitors are used in post-menopausal women with positive hormone receptor status.","Sentinel lymph node biopsy is the standard of care for axillary staging in early breast cancer."],"references":["Waks AG, Winer EP. Breast Cancer Treatment: A Review.\u00a0JAMA. 2019;321(3):288-300. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30667505/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"152"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T22:16:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T22:24:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"152"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"s